            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this caulk calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates how many tubes of caulk or sealant you need
                by calculating the volume of each bead and comparing it to the
                volume of one tube. It supports:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Round beads (roughly circular cross-section)</li>
                <li>Fillet beads in corners (triangular cross-section)</li>
                <li>Imperial and metric units</li>
                <li>Multiple joints with different dimensions</li>
                <li>Custom tube sizes and waste allowance</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <p>All calculations are based on simple geometry.</p>

              <h3>1. Round bead volume</h3>
              <p>
                For a round bead with diameter \(d\) and length \(L\), the
                cross-section is a circle:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Area of circle: \( A = \pi \left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^2 \)</p>
                <p>
                  Bead volume: \( V = A \cdot L = \pi \left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^2
                  L \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                In the calculator, we approximate the bead diameter by the joint
                width. Depth is ignored for round beads because the nozzle
                opening and tooling primarily control the diameter.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Fillet bead volume (corner joint)</h3>
              <p>
                A fillet bead in a 90° corner is approximately a right triangle
                in cross-section with leg length \(w\) (joint width along each
                surface):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Area of right triangle: \( A = \frac{1}{2} w^2 \)</p>
                <p>Bead volume: \( V = A \cdot L = \frac{1}{2} w^2 L \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Here, the depth field is treated as the same as width for a
                simple 45° fillet. If you want to model a different shape, you
                can adjust the width to match the actual bead size.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Tube volume and tubes required</h3>
              <p>
                Tube volume is converted internally to a consistent unit (cubic
                inches or cubic millimetres) using:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>1 fl oz ≈ 1.8047 in³</p>
                <p>1 ml = 1 cm³ = 1000 mm³</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Total bead volume is the sum of all joint volumes. With a waste
                factor \(w\) (%):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Total volume with waste: \( V_\text{waste} = V_\text{total}
                  \cdot \left(1 + \frac{w}{100}\right) \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Exact tubes: \( N_\text{exact} =
                  \dfrac{V_\text{waste}}{V_\text{tube}} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Tubes to buy: \( N_\text{buy} = \lceil N_\text{exact} \rceil
                  \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Typical caulk bead sizes and coverage</h2>
              <p>
                Actual coverage depends on product, tooling, and surface
                roughness, but the table below gives rough coverage for a 10.1
                fl oz (≈ 300 ml) tube with a round bead:
              </p>
              <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left">Bead diameter</th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left">
                        Approx. coverage per 10.1 fl oz tube
                      </th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">1/8 in (3 mm)</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">~ 300–350 ft (90–105 m)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">1/4 in (6 mm)</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">~ 75–90 ft (23–27 m)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">3/8 in (10 mm)</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">~ 30–40 ft (9–12 m)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">1/2 in (12 mm)</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">~ 18–25 ft (5–8 m)</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                These values assume a fairly full bead and minimal waste. For
                porous surfaces or heavy tooling, expect lower coverage.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for estimating caulk</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Round up your tube count.</strong> It is better to
                  have one spare tube than to run short mid-project.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use backer rod</strong> in deep joints to control
                  depth and reduce caulk usage.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Keep width-to-depth ratio reasonable.</strong> Many
                  sealant manufacturers recommend a width:depth ratio around
                  2:1.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Account for irregular joints.</strong> Increase the
                  waste factor for rough masonry, stone, or uneven gaps.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How do I calculate how many tubes of caulk I need?</h3>
              <p>
                Measure the total length of all joints, choose the bead shape,
                and enter the joint width and depth. The calculator computes the
                total bead volume and divides it by the volume of one tube, then
                adds your chosen waste factor and rounds up to whole tubes.
              </p>

              <h3>
                What is the difference between a round bead and a fillet bead?
              </h3>
              <p>
                A round bead is roughly circular in cross-section and is common
                on flat seams. A fillet bead is triangular and sits in a 90°
                corner between two surfaces. For the same width, a fillet bead
                uses less material than a full round bead.
              </p>

              <h3>How much extra caulk should I allow for waste?</h3>
              <p>
                For clean, straight joints, 5–10% extra is usually enough. For
                rough, porous, or irregular joints, or if you are new to
                caulking, 15–25% is safer. You can set this directly in the
                calculator.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for sealants, adhesives, and sausages?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Any product applied as a bead from a tube or sausage can be
                estimated with the same geometry. Just enter the correct tube or
                sausage volume in fl oz or ml.
              </p>
